title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson 6 inch 32 Win.
postcontent:
I have 2 Smith & Wesson hand ejector 3rd model 6 shot revolvers, with 6” barrels. They are both in the .32 Winchester caliber. However, one of the two has the factory target sights and according to collector handbooks, units with the factory target sights are rare and worth 3x the normal value. This pistol is in nice shape
There are 2 of these for sale; one of them is fully functional and dry fires fine. It has not been shot in many, many years, and was part of an inheritance.
The second one is a revolver has no serial numbers hidden by the grips. There is a “G6185” that appears in front of the cylinder. There is another marking on the underside of the barrel, looks to be 894B. I can only guess that this gun was produced some time between 1905 and 1934, but can’t tell without further help from a gunsmith.
This one also has an issue with the cylinder retainer; it should stay back but the spring that holds it is apparently broken. The action moves fine if you make sure that the cylinder release is all the way back. This one appears to be a mod 4 version, and the other may be a mod 3; I am not sure.
The one with the factory target sights has been valued at $1,200, and the other has been valued at $400 once the cylinder retainer spring is replaced, so I am pricing both of them for $1,400, for a faster sale.
